initial_story: the aim of this paper is to provide a classification of multilingual andplurilingual electronic lexicographic resources which would enable, one the onehand, the implementation of quantitative and qualitative criteria to produce atypological taxonomy of lexicographical tools, such as dictionaries, as opposedto platforms and websites and, on the other, the distinction of multilingualand plurilingual resources in terms of their larger or lesser prototypingdegree. in addition to offering a thorough description of the differentresources, this paper also puts forward some parameters and typologicalproposals to define and demarcate a number of electronic resources,particularly multilingual dictionaries and portals, while also outlining, andeven questioning, the object of study of multilingual and plurilinguallexicography.
stories: This paper seeks to categorize multilingual and plurilingual electronic lexicographic resources, facilitating the development of a typological framework for lexicographic tools, such as dictionaries, differentiated from platforms and websites, based on quantitative and qualitative criteria. Additionally, the paper aims to distinguish multilingual and plurilingual resources by their degree of prototyping. Furthermore, it provides an in-depth examination of various resources, proposing parameters and typological frameworks to define and demarcate electronic resources, including multilingual dictionaries and portals, while also exploring and challenging the boundaries of the field of multilingual and plurilingual lexicography.

This study aims to classify electronic dictionaries and other lexicographic tools, excluding platforms and websites, according to a set of quantitative and qualitative standards, in order to establish a typological framework. The research also seeks to differentiate between multilingual and plurilingual resources based on their level of development. Furthermore, it conducts an in-depth analysis of various resources, suggesting parameters and frameworks to identify and categorize electronic resources, including multilingual dictionaries and portals, while also investigating and pushing the limits of the field of multilingual and plurilingual lexicography.
